{{Good article}} {{Infobox person | name = Helen Lee | native_name = 헬렌 리 | native_name_lang = ko | image = <!-- just the name, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{circa}} 1965 <!-- {{birth year and age|1965|df=y}}--> | birth_place = [[Seoul]], South Korea | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|df=yes|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | body_discovered = | resting_place = | resting_place_coordinates = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LONG|type:landmark|display=inline}} --> | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | citizenship = Canadian | education = | alma_mater = {{plainlist| *[[University of Toronto]] *[[New York University]] }} | occupation = Film director | years_active = 1990–present | employer = | organization = | agent = | known_for = | notable_works = ''[[The Art of Woo]]'' | style = | influences = | influenced = | home_town = | spouse = | partner = | children = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | signature_size = }} '''Helen Lee''' ({{Lang-ko|헬렌 리}}; born circa 1965) is a [[Korean-Canadian]] film director. Born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, she emigrated to Canada at the age of four and grew up in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]]. Interested in film at a young age, she took film studies at the [[University of Toronto]] and, later, [[New York University]]. While in university she was influenced by [[Gender studies|gender]] and minority theories, as reflected in her first film, the [[short film|short]] ''Sally's Beauty Spot'' (1990). While continuing her studies she produced two more films before taking a five-year hiatus to live in Korea beginning in 1995. After her return, she released another short film and her feature film debut, ''[[The Art of Woo]]'' (2001). She continues to produce short films, although at a reduced rate. Lee's films often deal with [[gender]] and racial issues, reflecting the state of East Asians in modern society; a common theme in her work is sexuality, with several films featuring [[Miscegenation|interracial relationships]].
==Early life== Helen Lee was born in [[Seoul]], South Korea, around 1965, but came to Canada when she was four, a year after her parents.{{sfn|Lee, Biography}}{{sfn|Jew|1991|p=41}} She was raised in [[Scarborough, Toronto|Scarborough]], [[Ontario]], having moved there in the mid-1970s.{{sfn|Jew|1991|p=41}}{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=26}} As a child, she became interested in black-and-white films from the [[Golden Age of Hollywood]].{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|pp=22–23}} She later wrote that the 1960 film ''[[The World of Suzie Wong (film)|The World of Suzie Wong]]'' spoke to her racial identity as an Asian Canadian, an experience she found to have influenced her filmmaking;{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1391}} excerpts from the film were included in her first short.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1399}}
Lee began her tertiary studies at the [[University of Western Ontario]], taking business, before transferring to the [[University of Toronto]];{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}} there she majored in English literature and film studies.{{sfn|Lee, Biography}} By 1989 she was attending [[New York University]] (NYU), studying under [[Homi K. Bhabha]], [[Faye Ginsburg]], and Mick Taussig,{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|pp=22–23}} with a scholarship.{{sfn|Lee, Biography}} During this period she was influenced by [[Trinh T. Minh-ha]]'s paradigms on women and ethnicity, as expressed in the 1989 book ''Woman, Native, Other: Writing Postcoloniality and Feminism''; these were later expressed in Lee's first film. She later described Minh-ha as at one point being her "ultimate role model".{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1395}}
==Early film career== Lee made ''Sally's Beauty Spot'', a 12-minute-long [[short film]] focusing on a [[melanocytic nevus|mole]] on her sister's right breast, for a film editing class at NYU in 1990. For the film she used a second-hand [[Bolex]] camera and edited it with a [[Steenbeck]] editing suite. She later recalled that she recorded the film while in her pyjamas.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=24}} The production cost a total of $4,000.{{sfn|Duran|1992|p=4}} Fellow Canadian filmmaker David Weaver described it as sexualizing Sally's body, something that Lee had not intended.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=24}} The film was first screened at the [[Toronto International Film Festival|Festival of Festivals]] in Toronto.{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}} After graduation, Lee spent time as a curator at the [[Whitney Museum of American Art]] before returning to Canada.{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}}
In 1992 Lee made the forty-minute long film ''My Niagara'', which featured scenes shot in Japan that were reminiscent of [[home movies]]; the effect was obtained by filming in [[Super 8 mm film|Super 8]] [[Kodachrome]], then transferring it to [[16 mm film]]. Filmed in [[Etobicoke]], Ontario, at the childhood home of co-writer [[Kerri Sakamoto]], the film detailed a young Asian-Canadian woman living alone with her father after the death of her mother. Scenes were also shot at the [[R. C. Harris Water Treatment Plant]] in [[Toronto]].{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|pp=26–27}} Fransisca Duran in ''LIFT'' writes that the film, which had a budget of $80,000, had a theme of cultural displacement,{{sfn|Duran|1992|p=4}} and Lee states that ''My Niagara'' was well received.{{sfn|Duran|1992|p=6}} That year she also released the three-minute ''To Sir With Love''.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=34}}
After ''My Niagara'', Lee took a position as a director observer on the set of [[Atom Egoyan]]'s ''[[Exotica (film)|Exotica]]'', while led her to enrol with the [[Canadian Film Centre]] (CFC).{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}} Meanwhile, she worked as a [[film critic|film]] and [[music critic]] for ''[[Now (newspaper)|Now]]'' and extensively wrote about films for other publications.{{sfn|Lee, Biography}}{{sfn|Duran|1992|p=3}} She took further studies at the [[Banff Centre for the Arts]] in [[Banff, Alberta]], before returning to the CFC as a director residency.{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}} She continued to be involved with the American company [[Women Make Movies]], a distributor of feminist media, which she had become involved with while at NYU.{{sfn|Jew|1991|p=42}}
In 1995 Lee released the 26-minute-long ''Prey'', starring [[Adam Beach]] and [[Sandra Oh]];{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=28}} she described the film as a "cross-cultural comedy".{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1390}} The film, which followed a young Korean woman who falls in love with a drifter, was a collaboration with [[Cameron Bailey]] and dealt with themes of racial differences, immigration, and social class.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=28}} The Canadian film critic and experimental filmmaker [[Mike Hoolboom]] compared the themes to those of the 1989 [[Hollywood]] film ''[[Do the Right Thing]]'', writing that had [[short films]] been respected it would have been a watershed mark.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=29}} That year she also released the three-minute ''M. Nourbese Philip''.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=34}} She then took a five-year hiatus, which she spent in Korea.{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}}
==Post Korea== In 2000 Lee released the 22-minute short ''Subrosa'', following a woman's search for her mother in [[Seoul]]. Intended as a prequel for an undeveloped film entitled ''Priceless'', the film was shot in several formats with a fifteen-person crew, hurriedly recording scenes in public locations. It extensively used character-centred shots, leading to what Lee described as an organic understanding of the character. It also featured on-screen [[sexual intercourse]], framed in a [[medium shot]], which Lee intended as a [[Sign (semiotics)|sign]] and not simply a [[sex scene]].{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=30}} Although ''Priceless'', meant as a sequel to ''Subrosa'', went through more than thirty drafts, it was ultimately cancelled{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=32}} despite interest from [[Alliance Atlantis]] and [[Citytv]].{{sfn|MacDonald 2001, Helen Lee}}
Anita Lee, co-producer of ''Priceless'', then suggested that Helen Lee make ''[[The Art of Woo]]'', a [[romantic comedy]] sponsored by the Canadian Film Centre; it was Lee's [[feature film]] debut.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=32}}{{sfn|Braun 2001, Art of Woo}} Starring Adam Beach and [[Sook Yin Lee]], the film followed a Korean-Canadian art dealer who finds herself interested in a [[First Nations|native]] artist but considers him unworthy as he is poor. Released in 2001,{{sfn|Braun 2001, Art of Woo}} the film was "slashed" by critics.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=33}} For example, Jonathan Crow, writing for the [[Rovi Corporation]], found the film "less fun and less accomplished than a third grade theater production".{{sfn|Crow, The Art of Woo}} However, its soundtrack&nbsp;– by [[Ron Sexsmith]] and [[Kurt Swinghammer]]&nbsp;– won a [[Genie Awards|Genie Award]] for ''Best Achievement in Music&nbsp;– Original Song''.{{sfn|Crow, The Art of Woo}} That year she also released the three-minute ''Star''.{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|p=34}}
After ''The Art of Woo'', Lee announced that intended to adapt Kerri Sakamoto's novel ''The Electrical Field'' and a "romantic thriller".{{sfn|Reel.com 2001, Interview}} However, neither film has yet been released.{{sfn|Lee, Filmography}} In 2002 she showed the [[video installation]] ''Cleaving'' at the Werkleitz Biennale in Germany.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1396}} She married around 2008,{{sfn|Hoolboom|2008|pp=22–23}} and that same year released the short ''Hers at Last'', about the interactions of two women in Korea.{{sfn|Ciné-Asie 2009, Hers at Last}} The short was premiered at the Seoul International Women's Film Festival as part of an omnibus entitled ''Ten Ten'', in celebration of the festival's tenth anniversary. The omnibus also featured works by fellow directors [[Byun Young-joo]] and Lee Su-yeon.{{sfn|Newsen 2008, Seoul International Women's Film Festival}}
==Themes== Race, [[gender issues]], and [[racial identity]] often feature in Lee's works.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1390}} The main characters, up through ''The Art of Woo'', are Asian women that are "caught up in some cross cultural encounter".{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1393}} She writes that she attempts to address these issues through her films in non-[[didactic]] ways, such that the "racial melancholia&nbsp;... are like seepages in the more obvious dramatic or comedic content".{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1393}} She contrasts her films with the 1993 drama ''[[The Joy Luck Club (film)|The Joy Luck Club]]'', which she considers a film with obvious, easily consumable, ethnic content.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1394}} She considers the stereotype of Asian women as seductresses, either demure "lotus blossoms" or vociferous "dragon ladies", to be a degenerative one which is "sometimes extremely offensive", but one that has "a cultural memory that demands [the viewer's] attention."{{sfn|Jew|1991|pp=44–47}}
Lee's works often include elements of sexuality in their characterizations. She writes that the main characters of ''My Niagara'' and ''Subrosa'' reach a greater understanding of themselves and their relationships after sexual encounters. She considers sex as "never the culmination or end point", but a [[sign (semiotics)|sign]]ifier for intimacy.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1389}} As such, she feels that the more intimate aspects of sex are best conveyed wordlessly, through how it is presented, although she concedes that "talky sex" can be appropriate for romantic comedies.{{sfn|Shimizu|Lee|2004|p=1389}}
==Filmography== All of the below are short films unless noted. *''Sally's Beauty Spot'' (1990) *''My Niagara'' (1992) *''Prey'' (1995) *''Subrosa'' (2000) *''Helen'' (2002) *''[[The Art of Woo]]'' (2001; feature film debut) *''Hers at Last'' (2008)
